he does not fare very well as a presence in the ^Comedy~. In fact,
it will be the 'loser' Guinizzelli, who receives such affectionate
and justifying treatment in another canto (^Purg~.  XXVI) with which
... this one is closely associated by its language and concerns. It
is Guinizzelli, ^not~ Cavalcanti, who will be presented as the father
of the ^dolce stil nuovo~, high praise indeed. The strategy of Dante
has been to grant Cavalcanti the palms of the crowd, but to reserve
